      "content": "{\"claim\": \"A systems collapse triggered by cascading failures in the interdependent palatial trade and diplomatic network caused the simultaneous downfall.\", \"mechanism\": \"The Late Bronze Age civilizations were tightly coupled through trade, diplomatic marriages, and resource dependencies (especially tin and copper). A localized disruption—such as a drought in one region or the loss of a key trade node—created a feedback loop of famine, elite infighting, and administrative breakdown that propagated through the entire network, leaving only Egypt's more autarkic, Nile-based economy intact.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Archaeological evidence shows that the palatial centers were destroyed over a period of several decades, not simultaneously, and that some regions like Cyprus actually experienced a period of prosperity during the initial phase of the collapse.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the dominant academic consensus view, drawing on complexity theory. It elegantly explains the synchronicity and why Egypt survived, but struggles with the asynchronous nature of the actual destruction layers and the evidence of prosperity in some regions during the early collapse phase.\"}",
