      "content": "{\"claim\": \"A severe and prolonged megadrought, evidenced by paleoclimatic data, caused agricultural collapse, famine, and mass migration that overwhelmed the palatial states.\", \"mechanism\": \"A shift in the Mediterranean climate system led to a multi-decadal drought that devastated the rain-fed agriculture upon which the palatial economies depended. Crop failures triggered famines, which in turn caused elite infighting, administrative breakdown, and mass population movements (the 'Sea Peoples' were climate refugees). Egypt survived because the Nile's annual flood, fed by monsoon rains in the Ethiopian highlands, was largely unaffected by the Mediterranean drought, providing a reliable agricultural surplus.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Paleoclimatic proxies from the Nile Delta and Ethiopian highlands show that the Nile experienced a series of unusually low floods during the same period, which would have caused severe famine in Egypt as well, yet Egypt did not collapse.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This account has gained significant traction in recent decades due to advances in paleoclimatology. It provides a compelling root cause but is criticized for environmental determinism and for not explaining why Egypt survived when Nile flood records also indicate drought stress during this period.\"}",
